A home cook wants a simple way to know what is inside reusable food containers in the freezer without opening them, by tapping each container with an iPhone to see and update its contents.[1]

## User story

As a **home cook** who freezes leftovers in unlabelled boxes,  
I want to tap an NFC‑enabled container with my iPhone and see the saved information about what is inside,  
so that I can quickly identify, update, or reuse the container without guessing or opening it.[2][1]

## Scope of the first test app

- The app will support a single NFC tag type (e.g., a basic NDEF NFC tag embedded in or attached to the container).[3]
- The app will treat each physical tag as a “container record” with a small set of fields:  
  - Container ID (stored on the tag)  
  - Food name  
  - Date frozen  
  - Optional notes (e.g., “spicy”, “for guests”)[1]
- The tag will store either the full data or a compact ID that the app uses to look up data in local storage.[3]

## Basic journeys to demonstrate feasibility

1. **Create / Write to tag**  
   - User opens the app and chooses “Add container”.  
   - User types food name, date, and optional notes.  
   - App asks the user to hold the iPhone near the NFC tag.  
   - App writes a new record to the tag (and/or saves it locally linked to the tag’s ID).  
   - User sees a confirmation that the container has been saved.[2][1]

2. **Read from tag**  
   - User opens the app and chooses “Scan container”.  
   - User taps the iPhone on the tag.  
   - App reads the tag, finds the linked record, and displays food name, date, and notes.  
   - User can close the view knowing what is in the box without opening it.[1]

3. **Update (Edit) existing tag**  
   - User scans an existing container as above.  
   - On the details screen, user taps “Edit”, changes fields (for example, updates notes or corrects the food name).  
   - App saves the updated record and, if needed, rewrites the data on the tag.  
   - User sees confirmation that the container details are updated.[2][3]

4. **Clear / Reuse container**  
   - After the food is used, user scans the container.  
   - User taps “Clear & reuse”.  
   - App either clears the stored fields or marks the container as empty and updates or rewrites the tag accordingly.  
   - The container and its tag are now ready to be assigned to a new meal.[1]

## Out-of-scope for this first test

- No multi-user syncing, accounts, or cloud backend in the initial prototype.  
- No complex data structures, images, or long notes on the tag; only minimal fields needed to prove read/write/edit.[3]
- No automation such as background scanning or system‑wide shortcuts; all interactions start from inside the test app.[2]

## Definition of “done” for the feasibility prototype

- The app successfully reads and writes to at least one chosen NFC tag type using an iPhone, including:  
  - Writing a new record from user input.  
  - Reading an existing record from the same tag.  
  - Editing and rewriting that record.[3][1]
- The dev/project team can consistently demonstrate the above 3 flows in a short in‑person or recorded demo using real tags attached to containers.[1]

